\(\renewcommand{\hat}[1]{\widehat{#1}}\)

05_sin_mid


  1. Question

    Below, on the \(ty\) plane, is a graph of \(y=\sin(t)+k\) with a random parameter \(k\) and, as a dotted line, the parent function \(y=\sin(t)\).


    What is the value of \(k\)?


    Solution

    When we add/subtract a constant from the output of a function, the graphical result is a vertical shift. Notice the parent function has extremes at \(y=-1\) and \(y=1\), so the parent function has a midline at \(y=0\). The child function has extremes at \(y=-2.7\) and \(y=-0.7\), and those values have an average of -1.7. So the midline is at \(y=-1.7\) and so \(k=-1.7\).

    For sinusoidal functions, the midline is at the average of the max and min. In signal processing, the midline is called the DC bias. For example, in Audacity, there is a function to remove DC offset.

    A temporal sinusoidal wave can be described precisely by 4 parameters:

    • Amplitude: half the difference of max and min of the wave.
    • Midline (or offset, or DC bias): the average of the wave.
    • Frequency: number of repetitions per unit of time.
    • Initial phase: where in the cycle the wave is at \(t=0\).

    There are other important parameters that are related to the four above.

    • Period, which is the reciprocal of frequency.
    • Angular frequency, which is radians per second, found by multiplying the frequency by \(2\pi\).

    Also, some waves are spatial (instead of temporal). In that case, the distance between peaks is the wavelength (\(\lambda\)). Spatio-temporal waves have both period and wavelength, which are related by the velocity (\(v\)) of the wave. \(v=\frac{\lambda}{P}\).

    https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sine_wave

    https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waveform


    \[k=\frac{(-0.7)+(-2.7)}{2}=-1.7\]

    Thus, the curve was \(y=\sin(x)-1.7\).
